1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 What is the Supreme Court?

The Supreme Court of India is:

Highest judicial authority
Guardian of the Constitution
Final court of appeal

📌 Mentioned in Articles 124–147

🔵 Composition
Chief Justice of India (CJI)
Other judges (number decided by Parliament)

📌 Currently up to 34 judges (including CJI)

🔹 Appointment of Judges
Appointed by the President
Based on Collegium system
Collegium includes:
Chief Justice of India
Senior Supreme Court judges

📌 Judicial independence ensured.

🔴 Qualifications of Judge
Citizen of India
Judge of High Court for 5 years OR
Advocate for 10 years OR
Distinguished jurist
🔹 Tenure
Retires at 65 years
🔹 Jurisdiction of Supreme Court
1️⃣ Original Jurisdiction (Article 131)
Disputes between Centre & States
2️⃣ Appellate Jurisdiction
Appeals from High Courts
3️⃣ Advisory Jurisdiction (Article 143)
President can seek advice
4️⃣ Writ Jurisdiction (Article 32)
Protection of Fundamental Rights

📌 Called “Heart and Soul” (Ambedkar)

🔹 Judicial Review
Power to check validity of laws
Ensures Constitution supremacy
🔹 Judicial Activism
Courts take active role in governance
Example: PIL (Public Interest Litigation)
🔹 Independence of Judiciary

Ensured by:

Fixed tenure
Salary security
Removal only by impeachment
